1
00:00:00,723 --> 00:00:22,882
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato

2
00:00:23,199 --> 00:00:28,045
Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa.

3
00:00:28,065 --> 00:00:32,310
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:33,792 --> 00:00:37,536
So I just want to talk about, eventually I'll talk about Rupa.

5
00:00:37,796 --> 00:00:48,869
But before we do that, I thought we'd try to understand these different words that the Buddha uses to describe our condition.

6
00:00:49,340 --> 00:00:54,326
He talks about the all, and so I coined a word, his omniscape.

7
00:00:56,570 --> 00:00:59,554
And he uses three words to sort of explain this.

8
00:01:00,075 --> 00:01:04,100
The first one is ayatana, then there's indriya, and then there's dhatu.

9
00:01:08,447 --> 00:01:11,652
An ayatana is a sphere,

10
00:01:12,120 --> 00:01:19,480
There are various spheres cosmologically, all these different realms are all spheres.

11
00:01:21,224 --> 00:01:26,197
But for us as human beings, they refer basically to these sense bases.

12
00:01:26,887 --> 00:01:35,402
And the fact that these sense bases are unique and that they're discrete, you can't mix them.

13
00:01:36,183 --> 00:01:38,888
So, for instance, you can't hear through your eyes.

14
00:01:40,349 --> 00:01:45,838
And so some might say, well, what about synesthesia?

15
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:49,084
You know, where people see color and they hear this beautiful sound.

16
00:01:49,885 --> 00:01:51,409
But that's done by the mind.

17
00:01:51,777 --> 00:01:57,230
At the basic level of just that sense base, the retina can only see.

18
00:01:57,891 --> 00:02:00,197
It can only be sensitive to photons.

19
00:02:00,316 --> 00:02:02,822
It's not sensitive to airwaves.

20
00:02:05,227 --> 00:02:08,115
So that's what he means by an ayatana.

21
00:02:08,449 --> 00:02:36,330
and there are six of them so there's five, remember the five senses and the mind itself as a sense base so the mind is not the mind as a sense base is basically for your thoughts and emotions but it also works as a sort of channel that information comes from the other five and it runs through the sense base of manas and into the mind and then the mind creates something

22
00:02:43,381 --> 00:02:47,925
And when he's describing Nibbana, of course, he uses this word, ayatana.

23
00:02:48,045 --> 00:02:51,568
It's an ayatana, the dimension, the sphere, etc.

24
00:02:51,709 --> 00:02:52,610
So that's one thing.

25
00:02:53,290 --> 00:02:58,395
So he's, remember, he's always deconstructing and he's always trying to show us where the problem lies.

26
00:03:01,378 --> 00:03:01,479
Okay?

27
00:03:01,498 --> 00:03:08,906
So the problem lies in the ayatana of not recognizing that they are discrete, that they don't actually communicate with each other.

28
00:03:09,266 --> 00:03:12,509
That's all done through the cleverness, the magic of the mind.

29
00:03:17,097 --> 00:03:24,424
The next one is indriya, which means a power, or better still when it comes to the senses, a faculty.

30
00:03:24,764 --> 00:03:25,724
It's your faculties.

31
00:03:27,086 --> 00:03:29,549
And they're controlling principles.

32
00:03:30,049 --> 00:03:32,852
They direct force.

33
00:03:32,872 --> 00:03:44,203
So your cakindriya, your eye indriya, your eye faculty, is a way in through this ability to see the world.

34
00:03:44,963 --> 00:03:46,344
It's a faculty, it's a power.

35
00:03:48,704 --> 00:03:58,538
And actually, there's 22 of them, but we don't want to go into them because it does get a bit strange for us.

36
