See, my cheeks are heat at the moment.

209
00:20:21,707 --> 00:20:22,968
They're very hot.

210
00:20:22,988 --> 00:20:30,297
So the idea of fire, something that warms, interestingly enough, that ages.

211
00:20:31,159 --> 00:20:34,001
There's a connection there between fire...

212
00:20:33,981 --> 00:20:36,767
The burning out, the destruction of.

213
00:20:37,247 --> 00:20:39,711
So it's something that ages and destroys.

214
00:20:41,534 --> 00:20:47,163
So both the internal fire element and external fire element are simply just fire element.

215
00:20:47,183 --> 00:20:50,128
And that should be seen as it actually is with proper wisdom.

216
00:20:50,348 --> 00:20:50,990
It's not mine.

217
00:20:51,431 --> 00:20:52,211
It's not what I am.

218
00:20:52,251 --> 00:20:53,374
And it's not myself.

219
00:20:53,792 --> 00:21:02,045
And when one sees thus, actually with proper wisdom, one becomes disenchanted with the fire element and makes the mind dispassionate towards the fire element.

220
00:21:03,006 --> 00:21:06,852
So remember that when you're in your rooms and you're feeling a bit cool.

221
00:21:07,932 --> 00:21:10,457
It's just the fire element going down.

222
00:21:13,701 --> 00:21:15,243
No one is actually feeling cool.

223
00:21:16,944 --> 00:21:17,444
But there is.

224
00:21:18,506 --> 00:21:20,468
So the air element is much the same.

225
00:21:23,270 --> 00:21:25,251
Sometimes it's translated as wind actually.

226
00:21:25,873 --> 00:21:29,115
But the air element may be either internal or external.

227
00:21:29,135 --> 00:21:30,596
And what is the internal element?

228
00:21:30,676 --> 00:21:34,299
So belonging to oneself is air, airy and clung to.

229
00:21:34,820 --> 00:21:46,851
Upgoing winds, downgoing winds, winds in the belly, winds in the bowels, winds that course through the limbs, in-breath and out-breath or whatever else internally belongs to oneself

230
00:21:47,049 --> 00:21:48,673
is air, airy and clung to.

231
00:21:48,712 --> 00:21:50,194
This is the internal air element.

232
00:21:50,816 --> 00:21:57,807
So I don't know about winds going up and winds going down, but... We'll do the breath, shall we?

233
00:21:57,827 --> 00:21:58,848
We'll do the breath.

234
00:21:58,888 --> 00:22:00,111
We'll do the breath.

235
00:22:00,131 --> 00:22:01,272
Thank you.

236
00:22:01,292 --> 00:22:01,373
Yes.

237
00:22:02,595 --> 00:22:06,682
I won't worry about trying to feel the upward wind and downward wind, but definitely you can feel the breath.

238
00:22:06,981 --> 00:22:09,145
That's wind, the wind element.

239
00:22:09,165 --> 00:22:09,606
Airiness.

240
00:22:09,807 --> 00:22:11,148
Actually, it's just movement, isn't it?

241
00:22:11,169 --> 00:22:12,872
It's movement, wind element.

242
00:22:15,265 --> 00:22:16,689
And that should be seen as it properly is.

243
00:22:16,729 --> 00:22:19,276
So this is not mine, it's not myself, etc.

244
00:22:19,817 --> 00:22:23,748
So what one sees with proper wisdom, you become disenchanted.

245
00:22:24,229 --> 00:22:25,291
Disenchanted.

246
00:22:26,115 --> 00:22:34,967
So what is it we want from the world of things, the physical world?

247
00:22:35,928 --> 00:22:36,828
It's pleasure, isn't it?

248
00:22:37,329 --> 00:22:38,351
It's a pleasurable thing.

249
00:22:38,811 --> 00:22:41,555
And when we feel pleasurable things, we feel happy.

250
00:22:43,136 --> 00:22:43,718
We feel happy.

251
00:22:44,038 --> 00:22:55,531
That happiness can't be real in any sense of any duration, of any solidity, because when the object that's pleasant disappears, then the happiness disappears with it.

252
00:22:55,511 --> 00:22:59,738
And because it's clung to, you get that desire for more, etc., etc.

253
00:22:59,877 --> 00:23:00,578
We all know that.

254
00:23:00,598 --> 00:23:09,912
So this disenchantment is a different way of relating to that which is pleasant in the physical world.

255
00:23:10,792 --> 00:23:13,175
And we don't expect anything of it.

256
00:23:13,355 --> 00:23:13,957
It just is.

257
00:23:14,217 --> 00:23:16,180
So when we eat, if it's pleasant, it's pleasant.

258
00:23:16,339 --> 00:23:18,143
We don't expect it to make us happy.

259
00:23:18,383 --> 00:23:18,923
That's the point.

260
00:23:19,785 --> 00:23:21,067
Although happiness may arise.

261
00:23:21,587 --> 00:23:24,230
And that allows us to be dispassionate towards it.

262
00:23:24,250 --> 00:23:24,912
In other words...

263
00:23:25,297 --> 00:23:47,118
when somebody says to you let's go for a pizza you don't jump up and down too much so now if we go backtrack a little bit so we're back now to the earth element and we're looking at now there comes a time when the water element is disturbed

264
00:23:47,217 --> 00:24:15,958
and then the external element vanishes so this is to do with the cycles of the earth where the earth is destroyed first by water then by wind and then by fire so these are a huge sort of cyclic motions that eastern people would think much more in terms of cycles rather than this idea of progress that we have starting somewhere back there and we're going somewhere

265
00:24:15,938 --> 00:24:21,625
And one of the great shocks of spiritual practice is to find that we're actually going nowhere.

266
00:24:22,686 --> 00:24:36,006
So there's two ways of looking at time, the sort of repetitious turning around, you know, the day rising, the sun rises, the sun falls, and the idea of sort of time moving forward.

267
00:24:40,086 --> 00:24:51,990
When even this external earth element, great as it is, is seen to be impermanent, subject to destruction, disappearance and change, what of this body, which is clung to by craving and lasts but a while?

268
00:24:52,711 --> 00:24:57,740
There can be no considering that this is I, mine or I am.

269
00:24:58,750 --> 00:25:02,354
So there's a connection there between the fact that these elements disappear.

270
00:25:02,894 --> 00:25:08,221
So it's ridiculous to have some sort of relationship with them of identity, possession or conceit.

271
00:25:09,403 --> 00:25:16,892
So now he gives an example of how this might actually manifest through personal experience.

272
00:25:16,932 --> 00:25:21,417
So here we have a monk who very bravely has gone amongst people who don't like him.

273
00:25:22,098 --> 00:25:23,339
And this is what happens to him.

274
00:25:24,400 --> 00:25:31,371
If others abuse, revile, scold and harass a bhikkhu who has seen this element as it actually is, he understands thus.

275
00:25:31,892 --> 00:25:34,836
This painful feeling, born of ear contact, has arisen in me.

276
00:25:35,518 --> 00:25:37,320
This is dependent, not independent.

277
00:25:37,500 --> 00:25:38,402
Dependent on what?

278
00:25:38,481 --> 00:25:39,584
Dependent on contact.

279
00:25:40,085 --> 00:25:42,067
Then he sees the contact is impermanent.

280
00:25:42,228 --> 00:25:43,450
That feeling is impermanent.

281
00:25:43,810 --> 00:25:44,972
Perception is impermanent.

282
00:25:45,093 --> 00:25:46,214
Formation is impermanent.

283
00:25:46,615 --> 00:25:47,737
Consciousness is impermanent.

284
00:25:48,038 --> 00:25:51,403
And his mind, having the element of its object supported,

285
00:25:51,383 --> 00:25:57,869
enters into a new objective support and acquires confidence.

286
00:25:57,890 --> 00:25:58,651
That's where we're going.

287
00:26:01,835 --> 00:26:18,133
Then, if others attack a bhikkhu in ways that are unwished for, undesired and disagreeable, by contact with fists, clods, knives, sticks, he understands thus, this body is of a nature of contact with fists, clods, sticks and knives.

288
00:26:18,551 --> 00:26:23,577
But this has been said by the Blessed One in his advice on the simile of the saw.

289
00:26:23,657 --> 00:26:24,719
This is a very famous simile.

290
00:26:25,640 --> 00:26:42,117
Because if bandits were to sever you savagely limb from limb by a two-handed saw, he who gave rise to a mind of hate towards those who would carry out towards them would not be carrying out my teaching.

291
00:26:43,640 --> 00:26:47,984
Once when I said this in a talk, somebody said, well, the Buddha had a great sense of humour.

292
00:26:50,851 --> 00:26:55,336
So tireless energy shall be aroused in me and unremitting mindfulness established.

293
00:26:55,777 --> 00:27:00,883
My body shall be tranquil and untroubled, my mind concentrated and unified.

294
00:27:01,564 --> 00:27:10,974
And now let contact with fists, clods, sticks and knives assail this body for the teaching of the Buddhas has been practiced by me.

295
00:27:11,654 --> 00:27:12,596
So remember that, yeah?

296
00:27:12,737 --> 00:27:17,382
The next time you're attacked, this is just a club.

297
00:27:20,550 --> 00:27:22,613
And then finally,

298
00:27:23,150 --> 00:27:33,865
When the Bhikkhu then recollects the Buddha, Dhamma, Sangha, if equanimity supported by the wholesomeness does not establish in him, then he arouses a sense of urgency.

299
00:27:34,527 --> 00:27:36,469
This lovely sense of sambhaga, urgency.

300
00:27:36,489 --> 00:27:37,611
I've got to do something about this.

301
00:27:38,352 --> 00:27:39,394
It is a loss for me.

302
00:27:39,453 --> 00:27:40,895
It is no gain for me.

303
00:27:41,096 --> 00:27:41,856
It is bad for me.

304
00:27:42,218 --> 00:27:43,098
It is no good for me.

305
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:51,351
That when I thus recollect the Buddha, Dhamma and Sangha, equanimity supported by wholesomeness is not established in me.

306
00:27:52,376 --> 00:27:54,480
Now we get a little bit of insight into society.

307
00:27:54,761 --> 00:27:59,952
Just as when a daughter-in-law sees a father-in-law, she arouses a sense of urgency to please him.

308
00:28:00,794 --> 00:28:11,836
So too, when the Bhikkhu thus recollects the Buddha Dharma Sangha, if equanimity supported by the wholesome does not become established in him, he arouses a sense of urgency.

309
00:28:12,931 --> 00:28:22,202
But if when he recollects the Buddha Dhamma Sangha, equanimity supported by wholesomeness become established in him, then he is satisfied with it.

310
00:28:22,222 --> 00:28:25,086
And at that point, much is done by the Bhikkhu.

311
00:28:26,428 --> 00:28:33,116
So it's a case of also recognizing that there's a sort of practical element of this, you know.

312
00:28:35,662 --> 00:28:42,712
You know, just people who undergo operations, losing limbs, etc., faculties.

313
00:28:43,233 --> 00:28:56,994
See, this is one way that in the spiritual life they can become not so affected by it, by recognizing this body is just a vehicle, etc.,

314
00:28:57,615 --> 00:29:17,785
when we've got a headache you see it's just the thumping in the head pain when you go into the pain this is the whole this is the whole thing about vipassana situation that you're deconstructing going down to these mahabhutas down to these basic elements so remember when pain comes physical pain

315
00:29:18,727 --> 00:29:23,335
The clung to business, the upadana, manifests as your relationship to it.

316
00:29:23,355 --> 00:29:26,339
So as soon as the pain gets to a point, you want to move.

317
00:29:26,839 --> 00:29:30,145
So there's an expression of your clinging, right?

318
00:29:30,165 --> 00:29:33,832
To this, the pain, this is my pain and I don't want it.

319
00:29:35,335 --> 00:29:37,919
So you have to wait, remember, until that passes.

320
00:29:38,038 --> 00:29:43,468
If you don't, then you're not dealing with the clung to and it remains as a habit.

321
00:29:44,106 --> 00:29:51,554
It's only when you actually wait for that to pass away that this dispassion arises towards the feeling of pain in the knee.

322
00:29:53,476 --> 00:29:54,517
That's a direct thing.

323
00:29:54,877 --> 00:29:58,681
Normally, well, we'll come to that in a minute.

324
00:29:58,701 --> 00:29:59,801
So there's your dispassion.

325
00:30:01,144 --> 00:30:03,746
There's your equanimity with this pain in the knee.

326
00:30:04,146 --> 00:30:10,553
And once that's been established, you can then go into that pain in the knee and begin to see these Mahabhutas.

327
00:30:11,713 --> 00:30:18,305
So you go in there and the main one may be that sense of pressure, very tight, or it could be fiery, it could be very hot.

328
00:30:19,346 --> 00:30:28,541
So you go in there and you feel that and you point to it and you look at it and you feel it and you feel it and there may come a reflection.

329
00:30:29,423 --> 00:30:34,853
You don't have to do it purposefully because just in the doing there is the seeing.

330
00:30:35,221 --> 00:30:37,343
But the reflection may come after the practice.

331
00:30:37,743 --> 00:30:47,094
But even there, while you're doing this, you recognize that there's an observer observing, feeling, feeling these sensations, but somehow isn't it.

332
00:30:47,894 --> 00:30:52,640
There's a sensitivity towards them, but it's not actually identifying with it.

333
00:30:54,001 --> 00:30:56,243
And it's catching that because that's your release.

334
00:30:56,805 --> 00:30:59,186
That's your liberation from suffering right there.

335
00:31:00,127 --> 00:31:02,510
It's not something mystical.

336
00:31:02,862 --> 00:31:12,818
You're liberating yourself from suffering, first of all, by recognizing the clung to business, which is the desire to move, which is the clung to business.

337
00:31:13,339 --> 00:31:18,648
Now, when you get right down to the fire element, it's one of identity, right?

338
00:31:18,669 --> 00:31:19,851
So I am the body.

339
00:31:20,031 --> 00:31:20,593
This is me.

340
00:31:21,153 --> 00:31:22,035
You might say, well.

341
00:31:22,488 --> 00:31:49,136
I know you see intellectually we know the body but I mean as soon as soon as you fall ill or death approaches us we freak out so the the level of freaking out is the measure of that attachment so these these exercises really have you know a point to them you see and after that you might reflect upon it so when I'm here of course I ring the bell you know so there's a half a minute reflection

342
00:31:50,061 --> 00:31:53,346
And that's the sort of thing that you might reflect upon just for a moment, you see.

343
00:31:54,608 --> 00:31:56,792
Of course, when I'm not here, everybody jumps up and runs out.

344
00:31:59,817 --> 00:32:02,761
Which is not quite the practice, right?

345
00:32:02,781 --> 00:32:09,231
And I would suggest that you might follow that, if only out of respect for the occasional person who actually wants to do it.

346
00:32:10,134 --> 00:32:11,455
Because it's quite distracting, isn't it?

347
00:32:11,476 --> 00:32:14,601
When you're trying to reflect and you can hear this person running for it.

348
00:32:17,095 --> 00:32:22,442
So it's the same with all these physical sensations that we have.

349
00:32:23,584 --> 00:32:37,582
When you go outside and you're walking around, and you put your eye on the ground ahead of you, and you determine that you'll just be aware of what you're hearing.

350
00:32:40,006 --> 00:32:43,390
So as you're going through, as you're walking around the meadows,

351
00:32:43,453 --> 00:32:44,335
You're hearing things.

352
00:32:44,355 --> 00:32:47,079
You're hearing birds, the rustle of your feet, etc.

353
00:32:47,119 --> 00:32:47,661
Whatever it is.

354
00:32:47,721 --> 00:32:49,784
You might hear the traffic in the distance.

355
00:32:49,804 --> 00:32:51,066
So you're hearing, hearing, see?

356
00:32:52,449 --> 00:32:59,861
And then what you're trying to do is to actually begin to recognize that there's a sensation there.

357
00:33:00,442 --> 00:33:03,026
There's a sensation at the eardrum.

358
00:33:03,487 --> 00:33:04,548
It's catching something.

359
00:33:05,210 --> 00:33:05,529
Yeah?

360
00:33:05,864 --> 00:33:10,792
So this is prior to actually recognising what the sound is.

361
00:33:11,294 --> 00:33:14,721
So as soon as you hear the sound, of course, the mind says bird, so that you know.

362
00:33:15,602 --> 00:33:24,077
But the more you put yourself there, right at the ear door, then the more you're contacting that very moment when the sound comes in.

363
00:33:24,519 --> 00:33:27,765
Now, frankly, at that point, you don't want to be walking because you walk straight into the pond.

364
00:33:28,907 --> 00:33:29,188
You want to...

365
00:33:29,641 --> 00:33:31,222
It's good to do this when you're standing.

366
00:33:31,784 --> 00:33:42,200
So if you take a position at the back or somewhere to sit, which, yeah, there's only one place, I think, and that's in front of the Parinirvana Buddha.

367
00:33:42,601 --> 00:33:44,042
I'll try and get more.

368
00:33:44,844 --> 00:33:46,405
I'm not going to put seats out there.

369
00:33:46,445 --> 00:33:47,387
People don't put a seat.

370
00:33:47,847 --> 00:33:48,950
That's just for laziness, isn't it?

371
00:33:48,970 --> 00:33:50,231
You want to sit down for heaven's sake.

372
00:33:50,531 --> 00:34:00,561
But I'm hoping to put what they call, you know, in the churches where they have, they call them misery cords at the front where the monks used to sit.

373
00:34:01,082 --> 00:34:05,026
They used to be these, you'll see the seats, they fall down into a seat.

374
00:34:05,467 --> 00:34:08,809
But when you fold them up, there's a little ledge, right?

375
00:34:08,829 --> 00:34:16,177
So in the long sort of chantings that they used to do, they have a rest and they would just sort of sit a little bit on that ledge.

376
00:34:16,556 --> 00:34:19,239
That's why they're called pity, misery cord.

377
00:34:21,329 --> 00:34:25,155
These poor monks and nuns who had to chant for hours on end, you see.

378
00:34:25,175 --> 00:34:29,282
So I was thinking something like that, you see, where you can sit and you can do this sort of exercise.

379
00:34:29,983 --> 00:34:34,168
And you're constantly driving yourself to the point of contact, right?

380
00:34:34,750 --> 00:34:37,434
Point of contact.

381
00:34:37,454 --> 00:34:41,760
And that's where you begin to experience these sensations.

382
00:34:42,342 --> 00:34:46,728
So, for instance, the hearing, you see.

383
00:34:47,737 --> 00:34:54,411
you can actually experience that as a sense of touch on the eardrum.

384
00:34:55,112 --> 00:34:56,516
There's no sound there at all.

385
00:34:56,715 --> 00:35:01,465
You can actually get down to that point where all you're experiencing is like a tapping.

386
00:35:01,485 --> 00:35:06,456
If you were to tap your finger on the palm of your hand, it's something like that.

387
00:35:06,697 --> 00:35:07,418
That's all you get.

388
00:35:07,802 --> 00:35:08,985
And it's a drumming like that.

389
00:35:09,005 --> 00:35:10,927
And then it comes in.

390
00:35:11,688 --> 00:35:16,536
Now that's the only point where you've got the sense base.

391
00:35:16,576 --> 00:35:18,259
The sense base is that basic.

392
00:35:19,119 --> 00:35:25,690
The next point it comes through the manas, which is the mental sense base.

393
00:35:25,710 --> 00:35:28,815
And it's at that point of manas that it's turned into a sound.

394
00:35:29,925 --> 00:35:35,152
And then the sound is worked upon and it's given a meaning.

395
00:35:35,411 --> 00:35:36,213
So it's a bell.

396
00:35:36,974 --> 00:35:40,438
And then the bell is given a meaning, wake up bell.

397
00:35:40,617 --> 00:35:43,902
And then right at the end of that process, you get the identity.

398
00:35:44,402 --> 00:35:45,262
Me, I've got to get up.

399
00:35:45,764 --> 00:35:47,244
That comes right at the end of that process.

400
00:35:47,905 --> 00:35:50,768
And you can actually see that process, right?

401
00:35:51,250 --> 00:35:53,351
You might only see it once in a lifetime.

402
00:35:54,090 --> 00:35:55,092
but you can actually see it.

403
00:35:55,793 --> 00:36:06,253
And of course, to catch these things at that sort of level, you've really got to be, you know, really driven by interest and very, very still.

404
00:36:06,614 --> 00:36:07,896
You've got to be really still.

405
00:36:08,737 --> 00:36:16,572
So, without being too critical, you understand, I can see that meditators are relaxing, over-relaxing.

406
00:36:16,972 --> 00:36:18,494
So this is...

407
00:36:18,474 --> 00:36:20,117
There's got to be this constant effort.

408
00:36:20,378 --> 00:36:23,041
But remember, the effort is never to achieve something.

409
00:36:23,161 --> 00:36:30,572
It's always to maintain a certain level of interest and connection with what's actually happening here and now.

410
00:36:32,134 --> 00:36:37,081
And then, you know, you get these slightly deeper insights.

411
00:36:37,101 --> 00:36:37,961
Is it necessary?

412
00:36:38,123 --> 00:36:39,184
I don't think so.

413
00:36:39,822 --> 00:36:42,164
I mean, they're interesting things to have.

414
00:36:42,646 --> 00:36:45,710
They tend to support the Abhidhamma and things like that.

415
00:36:46,451 --> 00:36:48,853
But it's not interesting and it's not important, is it?

416
00:36:48,893 --> 00:36:55,541
Because here in the discourse, you don't get that sort of mincey little bit of deconstruction.

417
00:36:55,902 --> 00:37:00,108
You get a very straightforward sense-based deconstruction.

418
00:37:00,628 --> 00:37:06,836
So, for instance, as I say, if you've got a headache, the first thing is, you know, you just don't want it, you see.

419
00:37:07,077 --> 00:37:09,340
But if you relax and relax around it,

420
00:37:09,320 --> 00:37:34,197
and you use that headache that we call a headache and you go into it then you can see this tightness there's something that that constructs it and it's just that process of of disidentifying and deconstructing which is undermining this upadana this grasping so it happens there are many opportunities during the day when you can practice that

421
00:37:34,177 --> 00:37:37,701
And the more difficult one, of course, is when there's something which is pleasant.

422
00:37:38,081 --> 00:37:45,791
So obviously during mealtime, that's the time you've got to bring a certain sense of urgency, you know, that you're not going to indulge.

423
00:37:46,130 --> 00:37:48,875
You're not just there to be happy.

424
00:37:49,175 --> 00:37:50,717
You're there to investigate the process.

425
00:37:51,297 --> 00:37:54,981
So, you know, that's the process of tasting.

426
00:37:55,663 --> 00:38:00,528
So you're trying to get down beyond the idea of what it is that you're actually eating.

